    <thetext>I installed a Fedora 25 from a Live installation of Workstation (GNOME Shell) yesterday, then I decided to install also MATE desktop, thus I ran this:

   # dnf groupinstall \&quot;MATE Desktop\&quot;

It downloaded all the required packages and when it was to start it failed with vim-common conflicting with vim-minimal on one man page file. This conflict seems to be already fixed, but I didn&apos;t run `dnf update` right after install, I wanted to do it only after the groupinstall.

The groupinstall failed, but when I try to re-run it, I receive an &quot;error&quot; from dnf that the MATE Desktop group is already installed. It really isn&apos;t.

How can I convince dnf that the group is not installed, please? The groupremove is not an option, because it takes significant part of the system away.</thetext>
  </long_desc><long_desc isprivate="0" >
    <commentid>10201325</commentid>
    <comment_count>1</comment_count>
    <who name="Jaroslav Mracek">jmracek</who>
    <bug_when>2017-03-02 05:36:47 -0500</bug_when>
    <thetext>The problem was fixed in dnf-2.1.0 that is available for Fedora rawhide, but for Fedora24+ we have our testing repository that provides latest dnf updates (dnf copr enable rpmsoftwaremanagement/dnf-nightly).

Your problem can be solved by &quot;dnf group mark remove &lt;group-id&gt;&quot; that will mark group as uninstalled, but it will not remove any package.

Hope it helps.</thetext>
  </long_desc>
      
      

